  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and initiatives aimed at combating money laundering. These efforts are primarily driven by international organizations and conventions that set standards and encourage cooperation among countries. Here's a breakdown of some key ones:\n\n**Key International Organizations and Initiatives:**\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** This is the primary international body for setting standards and promoting the effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system.\n    *   **FATF Recommendations:** The FATF's 40 Recommendations are the internationally recognized standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. These recommendations cover a wide range of areas, including:\n        *   Criminalizing money laundering and terrorist financing\n        *   Customer due diligence (KYC)\n        *   Record-keeping requirements\n        *   Reporting suspicious transactions\n        *   International cooperation\n\n*   **United Nations (UN):**\n    *   **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** This convention was one of the earliest international agreements to address money laundering, focusing on the proceeds of drug trafficking.\n    *   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC) (2000):** This convention addresses money laundering related to a broader range of crimes, including organized crime, corruption, and terrorism.\n    *   **International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism (1999):** Although focused on terrorist financing, this convention is related to AML",
